@Node "CreateICMP"

    @{b}CreateICMP@{plain}

    Usage: icmp = CreateICMP(stem)
    <stem/V>

    Creates and returns an icmp header reading its fields from stem.
    The fields are:
    - DATA          the data of the icmp packet, needed to compute its checksum
    - TYPE          icmp type
    - CODE          type/code
    - PPTR
    - GWADDR
    - ID
    - SEQ
    - VOID
    - PMVOID
    - NEXTMTU
    - NUMADDRS
    - WPA
    - LIFETIME
    - OTIME
    - RTIME
    - TTIME
    - IP
    - RADV
    - MASK
@EndNode

@Node "CreateIP"

    @{b}CreateIP@{plain}

    Usage: ip = CreateIP(stem)
    <stem/V>

    Creates and returns an ip header reading its fields from stem.
    The fields are:
    - V         default 4
    - HL        default 5
    - TOS       default 0
    - LEN       deafult 20
    - ID
    - OFF
    - TTL       default IPDEFTTL
    - P
    - SRC       source ip addr in dotted form
    - DST       dest ip addr in dotted form
@EndNode

@Node "CreateTCP"

    @{b}CreateTCP@{plain}

    Usage: tcp = CreateTCP(stem)
    <stem/V>

    Creates and returns a tcp header reading its fields from stem.
    The fields are:
    - DATA     needed to compute the tcp checksum
    - SPORT
    - DPORT
    - SEQ
    - ACK
    - OFF
    - FLAGS
    - WIN
    - URP
    - SRC      sorce addr in dotted form, needed to compute tcp checksum
    - DST      dest addr in dotted form, needed to compute tcp checksum
@EndNode

@Node "CreateUDP"

    @{b}CreateUDP@{plain}

    Usage: udp = CreateUDP(stem)
    <stem/V>

    Creates and returns an udp header reading its fields from stem.
    The fields are:
    - DATA    needed to compute the udp checksum
    - SPORT
    - DPORT
    - SRC     sorce addr in dotted form, needed to compute tcp checksum
    - DST     dest addr in dotted form, needed to compute tcp checksum
@EndNode

@Node "crypt"

    @{b}crypt@{plain}

    Usage: cpasswd=crypt(passwd,set)
    <passwd>,<set>

    The crypt function performs password encryption.
    The algorithm used for encryption is implementation-dependent.

    The first argument is the clear password, the second is a salt,
    that can be created via GetSalt.

    Refer to usergoup.doc .

    Example:
    - generate a password from an user/pass:
      passwd=crypt(pass,GetSalt(user))
    - expression to verify a user/pass login:
      cript(pass,passwd)==passwd

    Returns the the cripted password.
@EndNode

@Node "GenesisGetGlobalUser"

    @{b}GenesisGetGlobalUser@{plain}

    GENESIS ONLY FUNCTION.

    Usage: res=GenesisGetGlobalUser(stem)
    <stem/V>

    Writes in stem the Genesis global user, if any.
    The fields set are:
    - NAME
    - PASSWD
    - UID
    - GID
    - GECOS
    - DIR
    - SHELL
    - FLAGS
    - MAXTIME
    - TIMESERVER    (not yet supported)

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "GenesisGetUser"

    @{b}GenesisGetUser@{plain}

    GENESIS ONLY FUNCTION.

    Usage: res=GenesisGetUser(stem,login,passwd,title,flags)
    <stem/V>,[login],[passwd],[title],[flags/N]

    Writes in stem an user from Genesis database.
    Open an "user request window" if the user must be identified.
    The fields set are:
    - NAME
    - PASSWD
    - UID
    - GID
    - GECOS
    - DIR
    - SHELL
    - FLAGS
    - MAXTIME
    - TIMESERVER    (not yet supported)

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "GenesisGetUserName"

    @{b}GenesisGetUserName@{plain}

    GENESIS ONLY FUNCTION.

    Usage: res=GenesisGetUserName(userNumer)
    <userNumber/N>

    Returns the name of the user number userNumber if it exists.
@EndNode

@Node "GenesisIsOnLine"

    @{b}GenesisIsOnLine@{plain}

    GENESIS ONLY FUNCTION.

    Usage: res=GenesisIsOnLine(flags)
    [flags]

    Checks or sets (if) Genesis (is) online.
    Flags can be one of:
    - ASKUSER
    - FORCE

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "GenesisReloadUserList"

    @{b}GenesisReloadUserList@{plain}

    GENESIS ONLY FUNCTION.

    Usage: res=GenesisReloadUserList()
    -

    Tells Genesis to reload the users list.
    Should be used after an application modified the user database.

    Always returns 1.
@EndNode

@Node "GenesisSetGlobalUser"

    @{b}GenesisSetGlobalUser@{plain}

    GENESIS ONLY FUNCTION.

    Usage: res=GenesisSetGlobalUser(stem,login,passwd,title,flags)
    <stem/V>,[login],[passwd],[title],[flags]

    Logins a new user and sets stem with the user fields.
    The fields set are:
    - NAME
    - PASSWD
    - UID
    - GID
    - GECOS
    - DIR
    - SHELL
    - FLAGS
    - MAXTIME
    - TIMESERVER    (not yet supported)

    Flags is one or more of:
    - ASKUSER
    - FORCE
    - STAYOPEN

    About STAYOPEN :
    Many applications use genesis.library to find out wich user
    is currently logged.
    E.g. YAM uses Genesis corrent logged user, if any.
    If you are using a different tcp/ip stack, you can still use
    this Genesis feature with this flags.
    It tells rxlibnet to stay opened so that also genesis.library
    remains opened and the user logged, till you unlog using this
    function with an empty user name.
    Of course, all that has sense only for non Genesis user :)

    See GenesisLogin example in the examples drawer.
@EndNode

@Node "GetGRGID"

    @{b}GetGRGID@{plain}

    Usage: res=GetGRGID(GID,group)
    <GID/N>,<group/V>

    Searches the group database for the given group id, stopping
    at the first found. Fills "group" with a group structure.

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "GetGRNam"

    @{b}GetGRNam@{plain}

    Usage: res=GetGRNam(name,group)
    <name>,<group/V>

    Searches the group database for the given group name, stopping
    at the first found. Fills "group" with a group structure.

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "GetPass"

    @{b}GetPass@{plain}

    Usage: res=GetPass(prompt)
    <prompt>

    Displays a prompt and read in a password.

    Returns the password read.
@EndNode

@Node "GetPWNam"

    @{b}GetPWNam@{plain}

    Usage: res=GetPWNam(name,pass)
    <name>,<pass/V>

    Searches the user database for the given name, stopping
    at the first found. Fills "pass" with a passwd structure.

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "GetPWUID"

    @{b}GetPWUID@{plain}

    Usage: res=GetPWUID(UID,pass)
    <UID/N>,<pass/V>

    Searches the user database for the given UID, stopping
    at the first found. Fills "pass" with a passwd structure.

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "GetSalt"

    @{b}GetSalt@{plain}

    Usage: salt=GetSalt(user)
    <user>

    GetSalt creates a text string that is suitable to be passed to
    crypt() as a settings string.

    Returns the salt string.
@EndNode

@Node "help"

    @{b}help@{plain}

    Usage: helpString=help(funName)
    <funName>

    Returns the arguments mask string of rxlibnet.library function "funName".
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiClosePF"

    @{b}MiamiClosePF@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: call MiamiClosePF(pfID)
    <pfID/N>

    Close a packet filter created with CreatPF .

    See @{"MiamiCreatePF" LINK "MiamiCreatePF"} @{"MiamiPFNext" LINK "MiamiPFNext"}
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiCreatePF"

    @{b}MiamiCreatePF@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: pfID =  MiamiCreatePF(dev,signal,maxPks)
    <dev>,<signal/N>,[maxPks/N]

    Create a packet filter and return its id .
    A packet filter will receive every in-out coming packet on
    the interface "dev" .

    "signal" is a rmh.library/AllocSignal allocated signal, that
    will be set any time a packet is received .

    maxPks is the max number of packets to store; it must be an
    integer greater than 1 .

    Returns the packet id or -1 for failure .

    Example: see pf.rexx

    See @{"MiamiClosePF" LINK "MiamiClosePF"} @{"MiamiPFNext" LINK "MiamiPFNext"}
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiDisallowDns"

    @{b}MiamiDisallowDns@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: call MiamiDisallowDns(1|0)
    [status/N]

    Disabled extern DNS lookup. Default for status is 0.

    Returns always 1.
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiGetPid"

    @{b}MiamiGetPid()@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: pid = MiamiGetPid()
    -
    Returns Miami's internal process descriptor as packed chars.
    This value is needed when you want to manipulates routes
    directly (see ip2if.rexx) .

    If you need just a Process ID (e.g. like in icmp echo packets)
    use pragma("ID") .
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiIFIndexToName"

    @{b}MiamiIFIndexToName@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    usage: ifname = MiamiIFIndexToName(index)
    <index/N>

    Return an interface name from an interface index .
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiIFNameToIndex"

    @{b}MiamiIFNameToIndex@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    usage: ifindex = MiamiIFNameToIndex(name)
    <name>

    Return an interface index from an interface name .
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiOnOffLine"

    @{b}MiamiOnOffLine@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    usage: call MiamiOnOffLine(interface,1|0)
    <interface>,[status/N]

    Switch the status of the interface. Default value for status is 0.
    The functions doen't wait for the switching to complete and
    always returns 1.
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiIsOnLine"

    @{b}MiamiIsOnLine@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: res=MiamiIsOnLine(interface,0|1)
    <interface>

    Tests if the given interface is online.
    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiPFNext"

    @{b}MiamiPFNext@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage:  pkt = MiamiPFNext(pfID)
    <pfID>

    Get next filtered packet .
    pfID is the packet filter id .

    See @{"MiamiClosePF" LINK "MiamiClosePF"} @{"MiamiCreate" LINK "MiamiCreatePF"}
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiPCapCompile"

    @{b}MiamiPCapCompile@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage:  filter = MiamiPCapCompile(expr,interface,prom)
    <expr>,[interface],[prom/]

    Compile the pcap expression for the interface specified,
    or the "suitable" one if any, with promiscous set if
    specified.

    Return a string that can be used with MiamiPCapMatch() or Null()
    for failure; the reasone of the failure can be found in "PACAPERR" .
    The filter can be freed with DROP .

    See @{"MiamiPCapMatch" LINK "MiamiPCapMatch"}
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiPCapMatch"

    @{b}MiamiPCapMatch@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage:  res = MiamiPCapMatch(filter,packet)
    <filter>,<packet>

    Match a filter created with MiamiPCapCompile() with a
    packet returned by MiamiPFNext() (or whatelse) .

    See @{"MiamiPCapCompile" LINK "MiamiPCapCompile"}
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiSetSocksConn"

    @{b}MiamiSetSocksConn@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: res=MiamiSetSocksConn(remote)
    <remote/V>

    Sets the destination address for the next SOCKS bind() request.
    Returns an ARexx boolean. remote is a sockaddr_in.
@EndNode

@Node "MiamiSupportsIPV6"

    @{b}MiamiSupportsIPV6@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: res=MiamiSupportsIPV6()
    --

    Tests if the current version of Miami supports the IPV6 protocol.

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

@Node "ReadICMP"

    @{b}ReadICMP@{plain}

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Usage: call ReadICMP(pkt,stem)
    <pkt>,<stem/V>

    Fills stem with an icmp header read from pkt.
    pkt must at least 28 bytes or an error 18 is generated.
    The fields set are:
    - TYPE
    - CODE
    - CKSUM

    (Yessss too lazi to make a better icmp parser  :)
@EndNode

@Node "ReadIP"

    @{b}ReadIP@{plain}

    Usage: call ReadIP(pkt,stem)
    <pkt>,<stem/V>

    Fills stem with an ip header read from pkt.
    pkt must at least 20 bytes or an error 18 is generated.
    The fields set are:
    - V
    - HL
    - TOS
    - LEN
    - ID
    - OFF
    - TTL
    - P
    - SUM
    - SRC in dotted form
    - DST in dotted form
@EndNode

@Node "ReadTCP"

    @{b}ReadTCP@{plain}

    Usage: call ReadTCP(pkt,stem)
    <pkt>,<stem/V>

    Fills stem with a tcp header read from pkt.
    pkt must at least 20 bytes or an error 18 is generated.
    The fields set are:
    - SPORT
    - DPORT
    - SEQ
    - ACK
    - OFF
    - X2
    - FLAGS
    - WIN
    - SUM
    - URP
@EndNode

@Node "ReadUDP"

    @{b}ReadUDP@{plain}

    Usage: call ReadUDP(pkt,stem)
    <pkt>,<stem/V>

    Fills stem with an udp header read from pkt.
    pkt must at least 8 bytes or an error 18 is generated.
    The fields set are:
    - SPORT
    - DPORT
    - ULEN
    - SUM
@EndNode

@Node "SockAtMark"

    @{b}SockAtMark@{plain}

    Usage: res=SockAtMark(socketfd)
    <socketfd/N>

    MIAMI ONLY FUNCTION

    Tests if the socket is in out of band status.

    Returns an ARexx boolean.
@EndNode

